The Linux Command Line Interface (CLI) allows users to interact with the operating system by typing commands. Unlike a graphical interface, the CLI provides direct control over files, directories, processes, and system settings.
Linux is widely used in servers, cloud environments, and cybersecurity.

Navigating the File System

pwd
Displays the current working directory.
pwd

ls
Lists files and directories.
ls

cd
Changes the current directory.
cd Documents

Working with Files and Directories
mkdir
Creates a new directory.
mkdir test

touch
Creates an empty file.
touch notes.txt

cp
Copies files or directories.
cp file.txt backup.txt

mv
Moves or renames files.
mv old.txt new.txt

rm
Removes files or directories.
rm file.txt

Viewing File Contents
cat
Displays file contents.
cat notes.txt

less
Allows viewing large files one page at a time.
less notes.txt

User Privileges
sudo
Executes commands with elevated privileges.
sudo apt update

Use sudo carefully, as it can make system-wide changes.


Many cybersecurity tools and servers run on Linux. Understanding the command line is essential for:

System administration
Log analysis
Security testing
Incident response

Key Takeaways:
The Linux CLI provides direct control of the operating system.
Commands such as pwd, ls, and cd are used for navigation.
Files and directories can be managed through the terminal.
sudo allows administrative actions.
Linux command-line skills are fundamental in cybersecurity.
